00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:54.000
You might be self-taught in R or your programming language of choice,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
like many others here,

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
and you might be struggling to figure things out on your own.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Or you might face resistance from people in your organization who say,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
R can't do that, R's not good for that, R's not a real programming language.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And it can be sort of jarring to go from environments like this conference

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.000
where you can see all of the amazing things that R can do

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
to being told that, no, it can't.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
So I have been there before too.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And I have also been the stubborn person at an organization insisting on using R

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
because I knew that I could be productive and build what I needed to build with it.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And having come out on the other side of that experience,

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.000
I can say definitively that I was right.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Not only is it possible to build quality software in R,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
I think everyone at this conference knows that,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
it is possible to have an organization where the strengths of R

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
and the people who use R can be brought to bear

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
to influence the entire organization and its mission as a whole.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So I work at a company called InsideRx.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And InsideRx, I think, is fairly unique in how pervasive R is to all of what we do.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So what I'd like to share with you today are the ways that we are doing this.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
How we're using R not only in production,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
but as a first-class language that is essential to fulfilling our mission.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
And to illustrate how we're doing that, I'd like to introduce you to Angela.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So Angela is a 60-year-old patient with a prosthetic heart valve.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And she comes into her doctor's office one day

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
complaining of having fevers kind of off and on over the last week.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
She's just not been feeling very well.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
And her doctor draws some blood samples and sends them off to the lab.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
But in the meantime, Angela is getting sicker and sicker.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
And she gets admitted to the hospital,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
where it turns out that she has contracted an infection called MRSA.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So if you've heard of MRSA before,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
it has likely been in these kind of like hushed, scary tones.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And that is because MRSA is very difficult to treat

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
because it's very resistant to many antibiotics.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:14.000
And so it carries with it this specter of antibiotic-resistant super bug scariness.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.000
But there are antibiotics that can treat MRSA.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And one of the ones that is used is called vancomycin.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
So vancomycin can treat MRSA.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
But vancomycin is very difficult to prescribe.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
It's very difficult to get the right dose for a patient.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And that is because with vancomycin,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
there is a very narrow window between what is enough to treat the infection,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
but not so much as to cause negative side effects,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
and particularly kidney damage.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
So you need to give enough that the infection is treated.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
But if you go too high, the patient can experience kidney damage.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And this is in contrast to some other antibiotics,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
like let's say an amoxicillin,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
where you might have a lot more leeway in how much you can prescribe.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
For vancomycin, that window is very narrow.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.000
And not only is it very narrow, it's different for every person.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:16.000
When you think about all of the diversity in people who might receive antibiotics,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
which is most people,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:23.000
there's so much variation in physiological characteristics

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
and all sorts of factors that can affect

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
how that drug is going to behave in a particular person's body.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:34.000
And so there's no one dose that is going to work for everyone.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.000
Angela may be represented by one of these bars on this plot,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
but a dose that works for her is maybe not going to work for me or for you.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So what we do at InsightRx is try to find the exact right dosage

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
of medications like vancomycin for every individual patient.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And we do this by combining peer-reviewed, published pharmacological models

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
from the literature, along with the patient's unique characteristics

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
and their data, their lab results,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
to find the dose that is going to thread that needle

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
and fit right within that window of enough to treat

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
whatever condition they're facing,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
but not so much as to cause negative side effects.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
And so to do this, we have a web application

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
that can access a lot of the patient's data,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
either having it directly inputted by their clinician

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
or brought in through their electronic health records.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
And so we get their height and weight, their lab results,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
past doses that they've received.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And we send all of that data to a REST API that's written in R

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
that can wrangle that data, apply these models,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
and identify a dose that is going to get that patient

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
to their target level of drug exposure.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So the goal level amount of drug in their system

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
to treat the condition that they're facing.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
And our REST API that's written in R

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.000
is going to send that dose, along with various other information

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
and plots and so forth, back to the web application,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
where it is then displayed to the patient's clinician,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:17.000
and they can use that in combination with their own expert judgment

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
to figure out how best to treat their patients.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So R is core to this product,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:28.000
because the entire point of its existence is to recommend these doses,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
and R is handling these most important calculations to do that.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And so because R is core to the product,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
that makes R core to fulfilling our mission,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
which goes beyond treating individual patients,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:47.000
but really towards elevating therapies for all patients.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And so at the next level,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
we have hospitals who want to understand

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
how their patients are doing as a whole, right?

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Are all of their patients reaching the targets that they want to achieve?

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
Are they having rates of side effects that are too high?

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Are there specific subpopulations

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
that are experiencing better or worse outcomes than others?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And so we want to help them answer all of these questions,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
and we can do so using data that comes from our NOVA application,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
the one that I just described.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
So we have an ETL pipeline that extracts data from the NOVA database.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
It de-identifies it, transforms it, and wrangles it in various ways,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
and loads it into our data warehouse.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And once it's in our data warehouse,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
we've then developed a second R pipeline

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
that pulls in the latest data,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
batch processes it to calculate these metrics

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
that the hospitals are interested in,

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.000
and loads it back into the data warehouse.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
So we've written a custom R package that can find the latest data,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
calculate all the things that we need to calculate,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
and save it back to the database,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.000
where it is then shown through dashboards and reports

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.000
to the hospitals inside our Apollo product.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
So we have NOVA, we have Apollo,

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
and then once we have this batch-processed data in our data warehouse,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:13.000
we can actually use it to refine the models that power NOVA.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
I mentioned that these models are published

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:19.000
and peer-reviewed models from the literature.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
Well, in our data warehouse,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
we have access to, in many cases,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
larger and more diverse data sets

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
than the original study authors had access to.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And so we can, in certain cases,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
refine and retrain some of these models,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
develop new models,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:41.000
and create other research that we feed back into the research community,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:44.000
as well as bringing it back into the platform.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
And this is maybe our most traditional use of R, right?

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
Because it's doing analyses,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
creating figures for publications,

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
writing reports,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
but it's no less crucial to the functioning of what we do.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
So R is a part of this entire process

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
of treating individual patients

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and improving, then, care for all patients.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
We have our REST API that's powering NOVA.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
We have our data processing pipeline.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
We have our analyses and new models.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
And we use R for many other things besides.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So I'll give just a couple more brief examples

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
to give you a sense of the breadth of the ways that we're using R.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
We validate all of our models using R.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
So we have implemented these models from the literature in R,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
and we need to make sure that our implementations

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
match what was originally published.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And so we've developed an R package

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
that can take outputs from our models

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
and compare it to a gold standard in pharmacometric software

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
and make sure that those outputs all line up.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
For regulatory reporting purposes,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
we need to verify that our software behaves

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
the way that we say that it does.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Not just the models, but the software as a whole.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.000
And so we have another R package

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
that can automate some of that process.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And then we use R, and particularly Shiny,

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
for new product prototypes.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
So within the data science team,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
we have both a lot of domain expertise

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
as well as the coding ability to be able to create

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
product prototypes for new ideas that we want to explore.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
And we can very rapidly develop these prototypes,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
much more so than if we were going back and forth

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
between one team with the domain knowledge

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
and one team with the coding expertise.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And there are many more options,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
but I will rein myself in at that point.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
But suffice it to say that R is crucial

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
to all of what we are doing.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
But I don't think it's a surprise to people here

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
that R can do all of these things individually.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
We know that you can create REST APIs

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
really easily with Plumber.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
We know that R is great for writing analyses

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
and creating reports in R Markdown or Corto.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
And we definitely know that Shiny makes it

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
incredibly easy to create awesome

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
interactive web applications.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
What is different here is the attitude of R

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
as a first-class language

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
and the idea that if we have a new problem,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
we can and are willing to solve it in R

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
just as easily as we might in any other language.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
And I think that that mindset requires us

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
to approach our work in a fundamentally collaborative way

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
because all of our systems that I showed in that graph

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
have components that are written in R

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
and written in other languages

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
that need to work together.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
So when we're developing a new feature,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
there might be business logic in our R API

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
as well as UI changes that are needed

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
to support that feature.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
And so in order to make all of this work,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
we have to work very closely.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
We're following the same release cycles,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
the same sprint cycles,

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
and adopting many shared practices

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
so that all of our pieces of this system

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
work together in concert.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And so as a result,

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
because our work is so tied together,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
when we have a new problem,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
we can be pretty open-minded about

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
who solves that problem and how we solve it.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And I think that that leads to better solutions overall.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
And so I'll give an example.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Our Nova application is used in multiple different countries

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
in the U.S. as well as in Europe.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And so it needs to operate in multiple different languages.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
And the way that we manage this,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
which is the way that many web applications do,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
is through localization files.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So localization files list out

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
all of the pieces of text that might appear on a page.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
And when the app is running in the U.S.,

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
it goes into the English version of the file

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
and pulls out the text that it needs to display

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:46.000
and puts it on the page.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
So at the Change My Password button,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
it's going to extract that text and put it onto the page.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And if the app is running in a German-speaking country,

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
then it will go to the German version of the file

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
and pull out that text and display it on the page.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And before every release,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
these files are professionally reviewed

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
by fluent speakers, humans.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
But in between releases,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.000
we need a way to keep all of these localization files up to date.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And the way that we used to do this

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
was that anytime an engineer made a change

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:19.000
that affected some text,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
they would edit the English version of the file,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
and then they'd copy their new text into Google Translate

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
and translate it into all these different languages,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:29.000
and then copy and paste it back into the other language files.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
And this was very cumbersome and tedious,

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
particularly if you're changing ten or more labels, right?

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
You have to translate all of these into multiple languages.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
And so my colleague and I decided

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
that we could write an R package that could make this easier.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
So our R package

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
will look at the English version of the file

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
and detect lines that have changed,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
text that has changed.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And it's going to send each of those updated labels

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
to a translation API

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
to translate it into the multiple languages.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:07.000
And then it can go to the corresponding locale files

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
and insert that text

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
exactly in the right location where it needs to be.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And so now an engineer doesn't need to

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
manually run all these translations.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
They can edit the English version of the file

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
and have the rest of the translations

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
automatically generated for them.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And again, before release, these are all reviewed.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
But this speeds up the development process considerably

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
and really reduces friction.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
And I think that this story illustrates

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
how R can be brought in to solve problems

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
that don't have that much to do with data science, right?

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
Because these are localization files

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
for a web application that is not primarily written in R.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
It's not primarily developed by data scientists.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
But we saw this problem and this point of friction

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
and because we had this mindset,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
we realized that there was no reason

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
that we couldn't use R to solve it.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
And in fact, we solved it very quickly and easily using R.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So our mindset of R as a first-class language

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
empowers us to solve problems.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
We felt empowered to solve this problem

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
even though it wasn't primarily a data science problem

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
because we know that R is a first-class language at InsideRx.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And sometimes the problems that we're solving

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
may be relatively straightforward things,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
like making it easier to work with localization files.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
But they can also be bigger things

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.000
that really affect patient care for patients like Angela.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
So let's check back in with Angela.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
Angela is in the hospital.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
She's receiving vancomycin to treat her MRSA infection.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And as I mentioned, with MRSA and with vancomycin,

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
if the dose is too high,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
it can cause damage to the patient's kidneys.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And so her doctors are regularly collecting lab results

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
to make sure that Angela's kidneys

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
are functioning correctly, healthily.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And we're using those lab results in our calculations

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
to determine what dose to recommend for Angela.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
But we realized that wouldn't it be nice

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
if we could actually alert the clinicians

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
in the event that Angela's kidneys

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
are starting to show signs of acute kidney injury.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So we have this lab data in the web application,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.000
and we could raise some warning in the UI

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
to let the clinician know,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
hey, you know, there may be a problem here.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Maybe they need to adjust treatment or take some action.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
So because we have this mindset of R as a first-class language,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
we know that we can do this in R.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
So we start with this idea for this new feature

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
and the mindset that we can build it in R.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
And then maybe we write some code

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
to detect acute kidney injury

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
and get something that works on our machine.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
But then to go from that to an actual feature

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
and a final product takes a little bit more work.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And how do we get from something that works on our machine

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
to that final product?

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
We have had to invest in certain practices

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:21.000
in that space between the prototype and the final product

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
to make sure that our work is reliable and deployable.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
So the reliability is important for many reasons,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
the most obvious of which being that

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
there are real human patients

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:35.000
whose health is directly affected by what we're doing.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
And the deployability is important

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
because we need a way to make sure that our code

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
and everything that it needs to run

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
can get to wherever it's going to run.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
And even for software that's not going to run

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
in its own standalone way,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
but rather things like reports that we generate,

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
it's beneficial to us to have a reproducible pipeline

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
to create those so that we're not subject

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:02.000
to the unique setup of one person's laptop.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.000
So when we're thinking about reliability

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
and how to detect kidney injury reliably,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.000
we need to make sure that we're detecting it accurately

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
all of the time.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.000
And the way to detect acute kidney injury, or AKI,

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
is relatively straightforward.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
So in everyone's blood,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
there's a waste product called creatinine.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
And a healthy, functioning kidney

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
is going to filter out creatinine over time.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
So ideally, my body's producing creatinine,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
my kidneys are filtering it out,

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
and that level is staying relatively stable in my blood.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
But if my kidneys are not functioning well,

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
then the level of creatinine is going to build up

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
and build up in my blood.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And so if that level goes up by a certain amount

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
within a certain period of time,

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
then that constitutes an acute kidney injury.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And so if this were a graph

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
of someone's creatinine measurements,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
they start to go up,

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
and by the time you reach the dot with a one on it,

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.000
the yellow dot,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
that's a stage one acute kidney injury,

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
and then there's additional grades of severity beyond that.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:13.000
So elevated creatinine suggests kidney damage.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:16.000
This is relatively easy to calculate in theory,

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:20.000
but in reality, things always get messy.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
You might have gaps in your data

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
so that you can't really tell

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
how quickly creatinine is changing.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
You might have data that comes in out of order

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.000
that you need to sort before you can calculate.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
You might have data that's reported in different units

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
that are totally different and need to be standardized.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
You might be missing the baseline creatinine values

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
for a given patient.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.000
So you know what their creatinine is now,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
but if you don't know where they started,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:52.000
then how can you tell how much that's gone up?

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
You might have data that's not numeric.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
I think anyone who has worked with real-world data

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
has experienced the phenomenon of data

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
that really ought to be numbers

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
coming in with other characters that you have to strip out

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
before you can handle it appropriately.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And there might be data entry errors,

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
either from the electronic health record system

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
or from manually inputting data.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:20.000
And so when we're trying to build a reliable feature,

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.000
we need to be able to handle all of these scenarios,

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
both now and in the future as our code changes.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And to do that, we add tests.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:32.000
So this is a test using the test that package,

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:37.000
which is in my top five most indispensable R packages

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
that I cannot live without.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.000
And in our test, we're going to lay out

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:43.000
the scenario that we want to capture

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:46.000
to make sure that our code behaves the way that we expect.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.000
So this is a test where we say that we're testing

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
that AKI stage is calculated correctly,

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:57.000
and we're going to run our AKI stage calculation function

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
with some sample data that we expect

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
should produce a particular result.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
In this case, it's a stage one acute kidney injury.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.000
And so then in the last line of the test,

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
we'll explicitly state that we expect

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:12.000
that the result of our function

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
is going to equal a stage one kidney injury.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
And if it doesn't, this test is going to fail.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:20.000
So we write these tests for all sorts of scenarios

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
that we want to capture, right?

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Different stages of AKIs, no AKIs,

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.000
data that looks, you know, in different ways,

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
as well as scenarios that we don't expect to encounter

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
or hope we don't encounter,

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
but would need to handle gracefully nonetheless,

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.000
like out-of-order data, non-numeric inputs,

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
missing observations.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
And once we have this collection of tests,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
we are sort of getting at all of our code

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
from many different angles to make sure

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.000
that it is reliable and it's functioning correctly

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:55.000
as long as we are running the tests regularly, right?

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Because if we're changing our code

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.000
and not rerunning the test,

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
then maybe we've changed some behavior

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
and we have no idea.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
So we need to run these tests often.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.000
And if I am disciplined, I can do that ten times a day.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
But I'm busy.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
Sometimes I'm lazy.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
I have other things that I would like to do with my life

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
other than run these tests all the time.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
And the reality is that

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:23.000
if we're relying on me to run the tests,

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
they're not going to run often enough.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Jenny Bryan once said that

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
if you use software that lacks automated tests,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
you are the tests.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Well, if we build software that lacks automated tests,

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.000
then that means our users are the tests.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
And by extension, they're patients.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
And so that is not acceptable at all.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
And this is where continuous integration comes in for us.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.000
Continuous integration allows us

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
to automatically run these tests

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
so that we are constantly making sure

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
that our code is behaving as intended.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:00.000
So every time we push new code to GitHub,

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:03.000
we kick off a pipeline that gets that latest code,

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:06.000
it builds the R package that it contains,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:07.000
and it runs the tests.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
And then it's going to send its results back to GitHub

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
in a way that we can clearly see.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:15.000
So if we were to look at the git history of our project,

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
we might see something like this.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
We have a commit where we add our function to detect AKIs,

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
and we write our tests along with that

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
so all of those tests are passing.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
And we get this nice green checkmark,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
which is very satisfying to me.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
And then maybe we realize that

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
the performance of our function is lacking.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
We need to refactor it in some way to make it faster.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
And so we rewrite it,

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:43.000
and we think that we've preserved its previous behavior,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:47.000
but actually we have changed how it handles some edge case

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
like how it deals with missing data.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
And so tests that used to pass start to fail.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
And our continuous integration pipeline

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:58.000
is going to send this angry red X back to GitHub,

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:01.000
which I find incredibly unsettling

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
and impossible to ignore.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
So because I'm alerted in this way

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:10.000
that is very, like, pings me right in the brain,

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
I can go in and fix the way we're handling

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
missing data in our function

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:17.000
so that the tests pass again

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.000
and I get my nice green checkmark back.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:27.000
So continuous integration allows us to find bugs quickly

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:29.000
because it's running automatically

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:31.000
as soon as we make changes to the code.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:34.000
It lets us free up time for more important work,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and it makes sure that our code continues to behave

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
as we intended.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
So testing and continuous integration together

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
are two of the practices that are most important for us

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
to ensure the reliability of our work.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:49.000
And then when it comes to deployability,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.000
we need a way to take our code

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
and all of the things it needs to run

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:55.000
and get it to some place

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
where it can run off of our laptops.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
And there are many different ways to do this.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
If you have access to Posit Connect,

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
that can make it super easy.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
In our case, we use Docker heavily

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
to be able to deploy our applications.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.000
So Docker allows you to package up

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.000
your code and everything it needs to run

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
into a self-contained little bundle called an image.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
So R itself, any R packages you need,

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
your code, any files your code needs,

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:27.000
all get wrapped up into this nice little bundle

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
that can then be sent off to wherever it needs to run.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:39.000
And we define these Docker images using a Dockerfile,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
and so I'll give a brief example of how this might look.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
In our first line of our Dockerfile,

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
we're going to say that we're going to start

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
with an existing Docker image

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
that already comes with R and Plumber installed.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
The RStudio Plumber, the 1.1.0 image,

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
comes with R and Plumber.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
And let's say we're building a Docker image

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
that's going to run a Plumber API,

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
so we need that package installed.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
So we're going to take this existing image,

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:09.000
and then we're going to add to it whatever else we need.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
So maybe we'll add another package,

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:15.000
like this open source package called clinpk that we maintain.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
And after we install our packages,

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
we're going to copy over our source code

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.000
from our project into the Docker image.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:25.000
So that's what this copy line is doing.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
It's copying over our code,

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.000
and then we're going to set our working directory

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
to where we've copied that code,

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.000
so we have all of our files nicely around us.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And then in the last line of this Dockerfile,

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.000
we say that when we start up a Docker container

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
based on this image,

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
we're going to source this entrypoint.r file,

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:45.000
which is going to run our Plumber API.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:50.000
I've put this example and a couple of others up on GitHub,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
so if you feel like playing around

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.000
with a couple of relatively simple Docker images,

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
Dockerfiles, you can check those out.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
But the important thing about this

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:04.000
is that someone could build and run this Docker image

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:07.000
without ever installing R on their machine.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.000
You don't need to have R.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:11.000
You don't need to have Plumber.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:13.000
You can build all of this and run this project

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:16.000
without installing R yourself on your machine.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.000
And so that makes Docker a really useful interface

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.000
between our data science team and other teams

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:26.000
because they don't need to know anything about R

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
to be able to build an R project,

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:31.000
and I don't need to know all of the tools

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.000
and background software for other languages

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:37.000
to be able to run those projects.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
And so when it comes to deploying our application,

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.000
I go to our DevOps engineer

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
who maintains our Kubernetes cluster,

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:45.000
and I don't know anything about

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:47.000
maintaining a Kubernetes cluster,

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:49.000
and he doesn't need to know about

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.000
what it takes to run an R project.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
If I can share this working Docker image,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
then that can be that point of connection

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
and collaboration for us,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:01.000
and that has worked really quite well for us.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.000
Docker is also actually an important component

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:07.000
of how we maintain the reliability of our code as well.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:10.000
So I mentioned that our continuous integration pipeline

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
gets the latest code,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
builds the R package, and runs the tests.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.000
But what it's actually doing is building the Docker image

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
that contains the R package

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
and running the tests in there.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:22.000
And this distinction is important

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
because the Docker image that it builds

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
is the exact one that we are going to run in production.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
It's exactly the same.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:32.000
And so we can eliminate any errors

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:35.000
due to package version mismatches

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:38.000
or subtle things that are different

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
in one environment compared to another.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.000
We are testing the exact versions of everything

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
that's going to be deployed in production,

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:49.000
and that gives us greater confidence in that reliability.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
So we've built our feature. We've tested it.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
Those tests are running automatically.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:56.000
Now we have our Docker image that contains our feature,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.000
and when it comes time to deploy the final product,

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
we'll go to wherever we're hosting it

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:04.000
and swap out the previous version of our Docker image

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
with the new one that we've created.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:09.000
And that gets us to the final product.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
So we started with this idea

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:14.000
that we could build this feature and build it in R.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
We wrote it.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
We adopted these practices

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
to make sure that it was reliable and deployable.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And now not only Angela,

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
but all patients can be monitored on an ongoing basis

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
and their medical teams alerted

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
if they are experiencing acute kidney injury.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.000
So I've shared some of the more technical aspects

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.000
of how we make our work in production for us.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.000
And I am aware that it might seem like a little bit of a lot.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
But for us, these practices are crucial

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:52.000
to make sure that we can run our in production

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
and have it be a functioning,

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:58.000
first-class system within our organization.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
And adopting these practices

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
also gives us as data scientists on our team

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.000
a greater connection to the rest of the organization

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.000
because we are all following a shared set of practices

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:14.000
and working together in a common way.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:18.000
And so we can bring our own skills and practices

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
that are useful to us as data scientists

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
to that equation as well.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
It's not just in the dashboards that we create,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:28.000
the visualizations and the reports that we build

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:32.000
that we bring value to our organizations.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.000
We as data scientists can bring our skills

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:39.000
to the craft and the process of building software as well.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
And that is something that I think a lot of other people

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:44.000
in our organizations can learn a lot from.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:50.000
So what are these skills and practices and mentalities?

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
The first one is that we as data scientists

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.000
are motivated to answer questions.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:58.000
I think that this is something that unites most data scientists.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
And it's something that we can apply

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
to our programming conundrums

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:05.000
just as much as to modeling customer churn

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:09.000
or whatever it is that we're doing.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:11.000
Debugging your code is essentially an exercise

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.000
in testing a hypothesis

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
where you observe some phenomenon

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
where code that you have written

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:19.000
is not behaving the way you intended

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:22.000
or is showing some undesirable behavior.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And you need to develop some kind of hypothesis

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:27.000
about why that is the case,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:31.000
gather some data that you can use in some way to analyze

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.000
and test that hypothesis,

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
and maybe conduct some experiment.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:40.000
So I'll give an example of a time where we did exactly that.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:43.000
In one of our applications that the engineering team maintains,

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:46.000
we had a database query that was too slow.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:49.000
It was taking too long to return data to a plot.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:52.000
Customers were complaining.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:56.000
And so the idea was to add an index to the database

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:01.000
to improve the performance of this query.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:04.000
So we added this index.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.000
And then the next day, our batch processing pipeline

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:10.000
that uses R to calculate all these metrics

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:14.000
that we show to our hospitals in our Apollo product,

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:18.000
that data processing pipeline was too slow to run.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.000
And it was assumed that because we had added this index,

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
that was slowing down the pipeline.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
And in theory, this is a plausible explanation

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.000
because when you add an index to a table,

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:31.000
typically it can make it faster to read data,

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.000
but it can make it slower to write data to that table.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:37.000
So we rolled back the change. We removed the index.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:42.000
And the next day, our processing pipeline was fast again.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.000
But the day after that, it was kind of slow again.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.000
So weird. I don't know. Whatever.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:51.000
A few months later, we had another issue of a database query

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
in a different part of the app that was too slow.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.000
And again, someone proposed adding an index to the database.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:01.000
But this time, the engineer who had to roll back that change last time

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:05.000
said, well, last time it slowed down this other thing.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.000
I don't think that we can add an index here.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.000
So now we're stuck in a situation where

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
our users are suffering slow queries,

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:18.000
but we are wary of making any changes that would improve them.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
And I was not very happy with this scenario

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:26.000
because I feel like whenever you're in a situation where you can't make changes

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
because you're afraid of breaking something,

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:31.000
that thing is already incredibly broken.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:36.000
And we, between our two teams, have control over this whole system,

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.000
so there's no reason that we couldn't actually figure out

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:43.000
whether the index was the cause of the slowness or not.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
No one had actually confirmed that.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
They just rolled back the change.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.000
So together with a colleague of mine, we ran a little experiment.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:55.000
We have a staging database where we can test out changes

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
before we make them to production.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:02.000
So on that staging database, I ran our data processing pipeline,

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
and I timed it.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:07.000
And then we added the indexes that we wanted to add.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:11.000
And then I ran that same pipeline again and timed it again.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
And I think that they were within milliseconds of each other.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
There was absolutely no difference in how long it took to run this pipeline

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
with and without the indexes.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:24.000
And so there was no reason that we couldn't add those indexes.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.000
So I share this story because I think it illustrates a time

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:31.000
when we could bring a data science mindset

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
and an experimental approach to solving an engineering problem

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
that would have been really difficult to answer

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:44.000
without some controlled experimentation.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:47.000
The next skill that we as data scientists, I think,

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:50.000
bring to the process of building software

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:53.000
and the work that we do as a company

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:57.000
is our ability to visualize and communicate our findings.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
A simple plot really does speak a thousand words.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:03.000
And I think that for a lot of people who have been in data science for a while,

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:07.000
it's almost second nature, and you can almost take for granted, right,

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:12.000
the ability to throw some data into a plot just to answer a quick question.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.000
But it's really an empowering skill.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.000
There's all kinds of tools out there for observability

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
and monitoring the health of software applications

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:24.000
that will show you all kinds of different charts and graphs and whatever.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.000
But when you have your own data and just want to see how it looks,

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:31.000
nothing beats the ability to do that really quickly on your own

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:37.000
without having to feed it into some external tool.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:39.000
So another example.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.000
Our DevOps engineer came to me and asked if we could compare

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.000
two different ways of hosting our R API.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.000
So we had it in one hosting environment in AWS,

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:51.000
and because it's AWS, there's like a million other options

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:54.000
that you could consider to run the same thing.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
And so we wanted to consider another one

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:00.000
that could also have hosted our API

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.000
but had different technical limitations and tradeoffs,

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:07.000
cost differences, and potentially performance differences,

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:12.000
which was what we wanted to look at.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:15.000
So again, approaching this like a data scientist,

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:17.000
I ran another little experiment.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
And remember I talked about the importance of adding tests.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:26.000
Well, in our code base, we have hundreds of examples of API calls

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:29.000
that we use in our tests to make sure that our code

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.000
is returning the results that we expect.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:37.000
And those tests then became the data that we used for this experiment

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.000
because when we are comparing two versions of the API,

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.000
we need some realistic test data that we can send to those

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
to time how long it takes to return an answer.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.000
And so all of these test cases became the data that I used,

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:56.000
and I sent them both to our two versions of the API,

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:01.000
and I timed how long it took to run each of them.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:03.000
And I plotted the results.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:07.000
So on this plot, the x-axis is our existing hosting environment

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:12.000
and how long it took to run each API call against that environment.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:15.000
So each of these dots is one API call.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
And on the y-axis, we have the second option

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:20.000
that we were comparing it to and how long it took to run against there.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:24.000
And you can see, based on the fact that almost all of these points

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:27.000
fall below that one-to-one line,

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:30.000
that option two was performing much faster than option one

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:34.000
or consistently faster.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:37.000
Now, to actually determine which one we were going to go with

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:40.000
of these two options, there's a lot more to dig into.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:43.000
There's performance under load.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:47.000
There's configuration tweaks that we could make to either option

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:50.000
to potentially improve things.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
There's the cost differences to consider.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:55.000
But the quick answer to is option two worth pursuing,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:58.000
this was immediate yes.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:02.000
And it took very, very little time and effort to create a plot

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
that just quickly captured that this was something that we should pursue.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:10.000
So again, we're bringing a data science skill

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.000
to an engineering decision or, in this case, a DevOps decision

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:20.000
in a way that really helps us move forward quickly.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:25.000
And then lastly, data scientists are used to dealing with uncertainty.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:28.000
There is uncertainty inherent in all of what we do.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
And I don't just mean statistical uncertainty,

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:34.000
although that is part of it as well.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:37.000
I don't know if any of you remember this website called Twitter.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:43.000
But my colleague once tweeted there that an underappreciated struggle

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:46.000
in data science is trying to not sarcastically answer

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
how many users did we have last month with,

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:54.000
that depends on what you mean by have users and last month.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.000
Again, I think this is relatable to many of you,

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:01.000
that this struggle to define the terms that we're even talking about

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
is a crucial part of data science.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:07.000
I mean, it might be like 80% of data science.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:12.000
So data scientists are used to digging into the weeds of this uncertainty.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
And when we are debugging code,

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.000
it can really be like debugging on hard mode

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:21.000
because the types of issues that we run into,

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
in many cases, are different than in more traditional software.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:31.000
A bug in a machine learning model may not translate to an obvious error.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:34.000
It might just degrade the accuracy of the model.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:37.000
So how do you even know if a bug is there?

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:43.000
It takes a lot of skill and dedication to uncover these types of issues.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:45.000
And that is work that data scientists are used to putting in

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:51.000
because the nature of our work is very uncertain.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
So I think that this leads us to kind of pull at threads

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:57.000
when we're solving a problem that other people might not consider

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:04.000
and allows us to bring a lot of creativity to solving those problems.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:08.000
So I think all of these things, our motivation to answer questions,

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.000
our skill at visualizing and communicating results,

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:14.000
and our ability to handle uncertainty

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:17.000
are all really important and useful skills

00:42:17.000 --> 00:42:21.000
that we bring as data scientists to our organizations,

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.000
wherever they may be.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:29.000
And they're things that other people can learn a lot from, too.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
So I hope at this point that I have convinced you

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:35.000
that using R in this way is working for us.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
It's not always easy.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:40.000
Sometimes it requires us to go outside of our comfort zones,

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:42.000
pick up some new skills.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:46.000
But in my opinion, the benefits really outweigh the challenges.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:50.000
Because by using R throughout our software stack,

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:54.000
we're enabling ourselves to do science throughout our software stack.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:58.000
And that is true both in what we build and in how we build it.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.000
So in the products that we build,

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:03.000
we are taking advantage of R's strengths

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:07.000
to provide the best therapies possible for patients.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:11.000
And in how we build it, in the process of how we're working,

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:14.000
we're taking on new practices that improve our own work,

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.000
making it more reliable and robust.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
And we're sharing our unique skills as data scientists

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:24.000
with others in the organization.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
So for those of you who raised your hand

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:31.000
when I asked if you had ever felt isolated or siloed in your work,

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:33.000
or if you're just looking for ways to take the things

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:37.000
that you're learning about here at this conference back with you,

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
I hope that I have planted a seed,

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.000
that it is possible to do this.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:45.000
It is possible to bring the bountiful ideas

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:48.000
that you are picking up at this conference

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
and share them with your organizations.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:53.000
And I hope that you will.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
Thank you.

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:08.000
Thanks, Kara.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:10.000
So hopefully you remembered.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:13.000
If you want to ask questions, ask them on Slido.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:16.000
While those pour in, I have a question for you, Kara.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:19.000
And that is, you talked a lot about using R at work.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:20.000
Yeah.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:21.000
Do you have a fun example of, like,

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.000
using R outside of work at home to solve some kind of challenge?

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.000
Yeah, I use R outside of work at home all the time.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.000
For a while, I haven't done this recently,

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
but for a while I was tracking my car's gas mileage

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
with a Shiny app.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:36.000
Because I, like, I noticed when I was, like,

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
filling my car up at the gas station

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:39.000
that it seemed like I wasn't, like,

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:41.000
getting as much mileage out of a tank.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.000
And so I would, standing at the gas station

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.000
while I was pumping gas, like, put data in a Google sheet,

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.000
and then I wrote this Shiny app to visualize

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:50.000
how my gas mileage changed over time.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
I do household budgeting in R.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
I feel like there's other examples, but yeah.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.000
I use R all the time.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:44:59.000
Okay.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:02.000
Hopefully Jenny Bryan is helping me out

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
filtering the Slido questions.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:09.000
So hopefully she is about to paste one in here.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:11.000
Well, it happens.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:15.000
Also, yeah, I use R a lot at home as well.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:18.000
And we use it, like, surprisingly a lot for this conference.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:21.000
Like, a lot of the information ends up in a Google sheet

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
which we can collaboratively edit.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
And we have, like, an R Markdown script,

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:27.000
a quarter script that, like, pulls it and displays it

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.000
in various ways.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:29.000
It's, like, such a great,

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
that combination of, like, Google sheets for data entry

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:35.000
and R for, like, exploring is, like, such a powerful combo.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:36.000
Yeah.

00:45:39.000 --> 00:45:43.000
It's very empowering just to, like, be able to do that.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:44.000
Okay.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.000
Jenny is typing into Slack.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.000
Okay.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:53.000
While CICD helps maintain consistency,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:56.000
how do you think about test coverage?

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
And how do you think about, like,

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:01.000
when behavior changes or models update

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
to the actual stakeholders?

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:05.000
Sorry.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
Can you say the last part of that again?

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.000
How do you update stakeholders when things change,

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:13.000
whether it's, like, model updates or changes to behavior?

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:18.000
So in terms of test coverage, I mean,

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.000
there's a variety of automated tools that can tell you

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:24.000
exactly how much test coverage you have.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
And so those can be really useful.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:29.000
But I think that for us, a lot of it comes down

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:34.000
to the social expectations and just amongst our team

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.000
reinforcing that when we're adding new code,

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:39.000
that we're testing all aspects of that.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:45.000
And so, like, I'm being, like, kind of pushy in my code reviews

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:47.000
to make sure that we are, you know,

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:50.000
testing things as we're adding them

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
and testing multiple different scenarios.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:53.000
So I think that there's, like,

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:56.000
a big social component to that process.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:59.000
And then when it comes to updating behavior,

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:02.000
again, I think with how we work,

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:05.000
because we're in the same sprint cycles,

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:09.000
we kind of have a lot of visibility across stakeholders

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:11.000
as to what new features are coming,

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.000
what changes in behavior are coming.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.000
And in many cases, those also have to be communicated

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:17.000
to the customers as well.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:22.000
And so when we, you know, develop a new feature,

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.000
we on the data science team develop a new feature

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:27.000
that turns into a feature in the application,

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:30.000
we might write up some, you know,

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.000
one-page explanation of what this is, what it means,

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.000
you know, how to interpret it,

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:38.000
that we work together with our customer success folks

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:42.000
to turn into something that can be user-facing as well.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:46.000
So there's a lot of kind of translating

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:51.000
and communicating in written form as well.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:53.000
Thanks.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.000
What about learning skills that are kind of traditionally

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
outside the wheelhouse of a data scientist?

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
Like, how do you go about learning Docker

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.000
and other tools like that?

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.000
Great question.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:08.000
I, in my experience, I peek at a lot of other packages.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:12.000
So I have various people on GitHub who I know

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:15.000
write good software or write interesting tools,

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
and I want to see how they do it.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.000
And so a lot of what I learn I sort of take from examples,

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:23.000
and that's why I put that Docker example up on GitHub

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:26.000
so that there is something existing

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
that is relatively simple

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.000
that people can play around with if they want.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:33.000
So seeking out examples,

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:37.000
especially from other programmers that you admire,

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
I think is a great way to learn.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
And some of it is trial and error

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:46.000
and some willingness to get your hands dirty

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:48.000
and just try things out.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:50.000
It's nice also if you have, like, a small project

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:52.000
that you can work on, I think.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:58.000
Like, for example, my gas mileage Shiny app

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
was how I taught myself Shiny

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
because I needed a way to learn Shiny

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
that was going to be fairly contained and simple.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:07.000
So I started with a small project that I was interested in

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:10.000
that didn't have a huge amount of stakes behind it

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:13.000
so that I could just focus on the learning.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:16.000
Along those lines, are there kind of any technologies

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:18.000
you've, like, learned recently

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
that you think have had a really big payoff

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
or, like, maybe have been really challenging to learn

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
but you think were worthwhile?

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:27.000
That's a good question.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:31.000
At work lately, I've been using Ansible a lot

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:32.000
to automate certain things.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:36.000
So our batch processing pipeline that I talked about

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
gets, like, scheduled through an Ansible job.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:42.000
We've got an Ansible job to run certain reports.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
That's something that our DevOps person set up

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
kind of for other purposes, and I was just like,

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:47.000
oh, that seems cool.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:50.000
I'm going to, like, do you mind if I just, like,

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.000
write some other jobs to do other things?

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:55.000
And he's pretty chill, so he was like, yeah, go for it.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:58.000
So that has been a pretty interesting tool

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:01.000
that I've been learning more about recently, yeah.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Can you share any tips for educating,

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:06.000
persuading people that you encounter

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:09.000
who, like, don't see R as, like, a first-class language

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:11.000
or as a real language?

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:20.000
Yes and no, I think.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:24.000
I think that my bigger tip is to try to ignore them

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.000
as much as possible.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.000
Yeah, thank you.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:33.000
Because it is, it can be, and to a certain extent,

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
if it's possible to block that out

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
and do what you need to do,

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.000
then it doesn't really matter what they think.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:40.000
But if they're the ones controlling

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
what you can do at your organization,

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
obviously that's a little bit tougher.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:47.000
And I think that that maybe gets back a little bit

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:50.000
to what Elaine was talking about in her keynote yesterday,

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
that if you can find a way to demonstrate

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
some value early on,

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:57.000
then maybe you can kind of reinforce and push

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
to get greater acceptance

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
once you've shown that R, in fact,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:03.000
can do all these things.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:06.000
What's your experience when hiring new folks

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:08.000
to how to, like, onboard them into this, like, mindset

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:11.000
of, like, go from not being not just a data scientist

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.000
but to learning a little bit about DevOps?

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:14.000
Like, how do you do it?

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:15.000
How do you find the people?

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
Oh, that's a great question.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
I haven't onboarded a lot of people

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:24.000
to this way of working so far.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:25.000
But I guess I have a little bit.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
And I think that when you can demonstrate

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:31.000
some of these tools that make it really easy,

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:33.000
like, Test.NET makes it really easy to write tests.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:37.000
There are tools that exist that make this work,

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:38.000
you know, not just a chore

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:41.000
but something that is actually fairly easy to do.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.000
And so when you can demonstrate that

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:48.000
and show how much time it can save,

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:51.000
I think that that kind of can get people into understanding

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
that this is a way of working

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:57.000
that has longer-term benefits as well, yeah.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.000
So I guess this is kind of a question for me.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:00.000
Like, as you've worked with, like, folks

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:03.000
from other languages and, you know,

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:04.000
doing their own kind of DevOps-y things,

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.000
are there things that you, like,

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.000
you see your colleagues using where you're like,

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:11.000
oh, wow, I wish there was something like that in R?

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:18.000
I'm not thinking of anything.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:19.000
I mean, R has really good tools.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:22.000
Thanks, Adly.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:23.000
I'll see if I can think of something,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:25.000
but nothing's coming to mind.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:26.000
Yeah, thanks.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:29.000
I'll take that as a compliment.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:32.000
Any tips for pitching decision support models

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:33.000
to senior business leaders

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
who often prefer to use their experience

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:40.000
slash gut feeling instead?

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:44.000
I do not have experience with that.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:47.000
For whatever reason, that's not been a challenge

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:49.000
that we've run into at InsideRx,

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
so I don't think that I can really speak to that one,

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:54.000
unfortunately.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.000
Okay, and I think we've got time for one last question.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:00.000
So what does your R data science team look like?

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:02.000
Like, how many people are involved

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:04.000
in building the package, doing modeling

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:07.000
versus, like, product prototyping or testing?

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:08.000
Yeah, great question.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:11.000
InsideRx is a startup, so people wear lots of hats.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:15.000
We have now one, two, three.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:18.000
So I'm on a team of five.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
I am the only person with the title

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:21.000
of data science engineer,

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:25.000
and then we have a number of data scientists.

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:28.000
And the breakdown can vary a lot,

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:32.000
so it depends somewhat on what people are interested in,

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:35.000
but typically I'm not involved in the modeling almost at all,

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.000
and the data scientists will be.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
When it comes to developing prototypes,

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:43.000
I think almost everyone has been involved in that,

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
but depending on the project,

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:48.000
it may not be everyone all at once.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:51.000
I am mostly the person responsible

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:55.000
for maintaining the continuous integration pipelines,

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:59.000
you know, maintaining our Docker build process,

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:03.000
and developing new features within our API

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
could be anyone on the team.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
I do it a fair amount,

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
but other data scientists do as well.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:12.000
Great. Well, thank you so much, Cara.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
Thank you.

